# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: qiskit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] This page shows how to use the Qiskit Aer `noise` module to build noise models for simulating quantum circuits in the presence of errors.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] This is useful for emulating noisy quantum processors and for studying the effects of noise on the execution of quantum algorithms.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] The Qiskit Aer `noise` module contains Python classes to build customized noise models for simulation.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] The `QuantumError` class which describes CPTP gate errors.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] The `ReadoutError` class which describes classical readout errors.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] You can initialize a noise model with parameters set from the latest calibration data for a physical backend.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] The `FakeSherbrooke` mock backend from `qiskit_ibm_runtime` is used in these examples, but you can try it on any Qiskit-compatible real or fake backend.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] This will yield a noise model that roughly approximates the errors one would encounter when using that backend.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] If you want to have more detailed control over the parameters of the noise model, then you'll need to create your own noise model, as described in the rest of this page.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] Rather than deal with the `QuantumError` object directly, many helper functions exist to automatically generate a specific type of parameterized quantum error.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] These are contained in the `noise` module and include functions for many common error types used in quantum computing research.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] We can also convert back and forth between `QuantumError` objects in Qiskit Aer and `QuantumChannel` objects in Qiskit.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] Readout errors may also be combined using `compose`, `tensor` and `expand`, like with quantum errors.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] When adding a quantum error to a noise model, we must specify the type of *instruction* that it acts on and what qubits to apply it to.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] This applies the same error to any occurrence of an instruction, regardless of which qubits it acts on.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] This applies the error to any occurrence of an instruction acting on a specified list of qubits.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] Note that the order of the qubit matters: for example, an error applied to qubits [0, 1] for a two-qubit gate is different to one applied to qubits [1, 0].
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] `NoiseModel` does not support addition of non-local qubit quantum errors.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] They should be handled outside of `NoiseModel`.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] That suggests you should write your own transpiler pass (`TransformationPass`) and run the pass just before running the simulator if you need to insert your quantum errors into your circuit under your own conditions.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] The command `AerSimulator(noise_model=noise_model)` returns a simulator configured to the given noise model.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] In addition to setting the simulator's noise model, it also overrides the simulator's basis gates, according to the gates of the noise model.
[src:qiskit/build-noise-models] We will now give some examples of noise models.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The Qiskit SDK includes a library of popular circuits to use as building blocks in your own programs.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Using pre-defined circuits saves time researching, writing code, and debugging.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The library includes popular circuits in quantum computing, circuits that are difficult to simulate classically, and circuits useful for quantum hardware benchmarking.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] This page lists the different circuit categories the library provides.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] For a full list of circuits, see the circuit library API documentation.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The circuit library also includes standard quantum gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Some are more fundamental gates (such as the `UGate`), and others are multi-qubit gates that usually need building from single- and two-qubit gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] To add imported gates to your circuit, use the `append` method; the first argument is the gate, and the next argument is a list of qubits to apply the gate to.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] For example, the following code cell creates a circuit with a Hadamard gate and a multi-controlled-X gate.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] See Standard gates in the circuit library API documentation.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] These circuits alternate layers of single-qubit rotation gates with layers of multi-qubit entangling gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] This family of circuits is popular in variational quantum algorithms because they can produce a wide range of quantum states.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Variational algorithms adjust the gate parameters to find states that have certain properties (such as states that represent a good solution to an optimization problem).
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] For this purpose, many circuits in the library are **parameterized**, which means you can define them without fixed values.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The following code cell imports a `n_local` circuit, in which the entangling gates are two-qubit gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] This circuit interleaves blocks of parameterized single-qubit gates, followed by entangling blocks of two-qubit gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The following code creates a three-qubit circuit, with single-qubit RX-gates and two-qubit CZ-gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] You can get a list-like object of the circuit's parameters from the `parameters` attribute.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] You can also use this to assign these parameters to real values using a dictionary of the form `{ Parameter: number }`.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] To demonstrate, the following code cell assigns each parameter in the circuit to `0`.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] For more information, see N-local gates in the circuit library API documentation or take the Variational algorithm design course in IBM Quantum Learning.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] These parameterized circuits encode data onto quantum states for processing by quantum machine learning algorithms.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The best approach depends upon the specifics of your application.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] On current quantum computers, however, we often use angle-encoding circuits such as the `zz_feature_map`.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] See Data encoding circuits in the circuit library API documentation.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] These circuits simulate a quantum state evolving in time.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Use time-evolution circuits to investigate physical effects such as heat transfer or phase transitions in a system.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Time-evolution circuits are also a fundamental building block of chemistry wave functions (such as unitary coupled-cluster trial states) and of the QAOA algorithm we use for optimization problems.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Read the `PauliEvolutionGate` API documentation.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Benchmarking circuits give us a sense of how well our hardware is actually working, and complexity-theory circuits help us understand how difficult the problems we want to solve are.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] For example, the "quantum volume" benchmark measures how accurately a quantum computer executes a type of random quantum circuit.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The score of the quantum computer increases with the size of the circuit it can reliably run.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] This takes into account all aspects of the computer, including qubit count, instruction fidelity, qubit connectivity, and the software stack transpiling and post-processing results.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Read more about quantum volume in the original quantum volume paper.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The following code shows an example of a quantum volume circuit built in Qiskit that runs on four qubits (the `unitary` blocks are randomized two-qubit gates).
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] The circuit library also includes circuits believed to be hard to simulate classically, such as instantaneous quantum polynomial (iqp) circuits.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] These circuits sandwich certain diagonal gates (in the computational basis) between blocks of Hadamard gates.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Other circuits include `grover_operator` for use in Grover's algorithm, and the `fourier_checking` circuit for the Fourier checking problem.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] See these circuits in Particular quantum circuits in the circuit library API documentation.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Arithmetic operations are classical functions, such as adding integers and bit-wise operations.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] These may be useful with algorithms such as amplitude estimation for finance applications, and in algorithms like the HHL algorithm, which solves linear systems of equations.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] As an example, let’s try adding two three-bit numbers using a "ripple-carry" circuit to perform in-place addition (`FullAdderGate`).
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] This adder adds two numbers (we'll call them "A" and "B") and writes the result to the register that held B.
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] Simulating the circuit shows that it outputs `5` for all `1024` shots (i.e. is measured with probability `1.0`).
[src:qiskit/circuit-library] See Arithmetic in the circuit library API documentation.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] You will first create a simple "Hello world" quantum program and run it on a quantum processing unit (QPU).
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Because actual quantum research requires much more robust programs, in the second section (Scale to large numbers of qubits), you will scale the simple program up to utility level.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Set up your authentication for access to quantum hardware through the free Open Plan.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] If you are using a public computer or other unsecured environment, follow the manual authentication instructions instead to keep your authentication credentials safe.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Execute using a quantum primitive function.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] In a quantum program, *quantum circuits* are the native format in which to represent quantum instructions, and *operators* represent the observables to be measured.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] When creating a circuit, you'll usually create a new `QuantumCircuit` object, then add instructions to it in sequence.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The following code cell creates a circuit that produces a *Bell state,* which is a state wherein two qubits are fully entangled with each other.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The Qiskit SDK uses the LSb 0 bit numbering where the $n^{th}$ nth digit has value $1 \ll n$ 1≪n or $2^n$ 2n.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] For more details, see the Bit-ordering in the Qiskit SDK topic.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] See `QuantumCircuit` in the documentation for all available operations.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] When creating quantum circuits, you must also consider what type of data you want returned after execution.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Qiskit provides two ways to return data: you can obtain sampling output for a set of qubits you choose to measure, or you can obtain the expectation value of an observable.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Prepare your workload to measure your circuit in one of these two ways with Qiskit primitives (explained in detail in Step 3).
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] This example measures expectation values by using the `qiskit.quantum_info` submodule, which is specified by using operators (mathematical objects used to represent an action or process that changes a quantum state).
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The following code cell creates six two-qubit Pauli operators: `IZ`, `IX`, `ZI`, `XI`, `ZZ`, and `XX`.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Here, something like the `ZZ` operator is a shorthand for the tensor product $Z\otimes Z$ Z⊗Z, which means measuring Z on qubit 1 and Z on qubit 0 together, and obtaining information about the correlation between qubit 1 and qubit 0.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Expectation values like this are also typically written as $\langle Z_1 Z_0 \rangle$ ⟨Z1Z0⟩.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] If the state is entangled, then the measurement of $\langle Z_1 Z_0 \rangle$ ⟨Z1Z0⟩ should be different from the measurement of $\langle I_1 \otimes Z_0 \rangle \langle Z_1 \otimes I_0 \rangle$ ⟨I1⊗Z0⟩⟨Z1⊗I0⟩.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] For the specific entangled state created by our circuit described above, the measurement of $\langle Z_1 Z_0 \rangle$ ⟨Z1Z0⟩ should be 1 and the measurement of $\langle I_1 \otimes Z_0 \rangle \langle Z_1 \otimes I_0 \rangle$ ⟨I1⊗Z0⟩⟨Z1⊗I0⟩ should be zero.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] When executing circuits on a device, it is important to optimize the set of instructions that the circuit contains and minimize the overall depth (roughly the number of instructions) of the circuit.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] This ensures that you obtain the best results possible by reducing the effects of error and noise.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Additionally, the circuit's instructions must conform to a backend device's Instruction Set Architecture (ISA) and must consider the device's basis gates and qubit connectivity.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The following code instantiates a real device to submit a job to and transforms the circuit and observables to match that backend's ISA.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Quantum computers can produce random results, so you usually collect a sample of the outputs by running the circuit many times.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] You can estimate the value of the observable by using the `Estimator` class.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] `Estimator` is one of two primitives; the other is `Sampler`, which can be used to get data from a quantum computer.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] These objects possess a `run()` method that executes the selection of circuits, observables, and parameters (if applicable), using a primitive unified bloc (PUB).
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] After a job is submitted, you can wait until either the job is completed within your current python instance, or use the `job_id` to retrieve the data at a later time.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] After the job completes, examine its output through the job's `result()` attribute.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] When you run your quantum program on a real device, your workload must wait in a queue before it runs.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] To save time, you can instead use the following code to run this small workload on the `fake_provider` with the Qiskit Runtime local testing mode.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Note that this is only possible for a small circuit.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] When you scale up in the next section, you will need to use a real device.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The analyze step is typically where you might post-process your results using, for example, measurement error mitigation or zero noise extrapolation (ZNE).
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] You might feed these results into another workflow for further analysis or prepare a plot of the key values and data.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] In general, this step is specific to your problem.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] For this example, plot each of the expectation values that were measured for our circuit.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The expectation values and standard deviations for the observables you specified to Estimator are accessed through the job result's `PubResult.data.evs` and `PubResult.data.stds` attributes.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] To obtain the results from Sampler, use the `PubResult.data.meas.get_counts()` function, which will return a `dict` of measurements in the form of bitstrings as keys and counts as their corresponding values.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] For more information, see the Sampler quickstart guide.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Notice that for qubits 0 and 1, the independent expectation values of both X and Z are 0, while the correlations (`XX` and `ZZ`) are 1.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] This is a hallmark of quantum entanglement.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] In quantum computing, utility-scale work is crucial for making progress in the field.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Such work requires computations to be done on a much larger scale; working with circuits that might use over 100 qubits and over 1000 gates.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] This example demonstrates how you can accomplish utility-scale work on IBM® QPUs by creating and analyzing a 100-qubit GHZ state.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] It uses the Qiskit patterns workflow and ends by measuring the expectation value $\langle Z_0 Z_i \rangle$ ⟨Z0Zi⟩ for each qubit.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Write a function that returns a `QuantumCircuit` that prepares an n n-qubit GHZ state (essentially an extended Bell state), then use that function to prepare a 100-qubit GHZ state and collect the observables to be measured.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] This example uses the `ZZ` operators between qubits to examine the behavior as they get farther apart.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Increasingly inaccurate (corrupted) expectation values between distant qubits would reveal the level of noise present.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The following code transforms the circuit and observables to match the backend's ISA.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Submit the job and enable error suppression by using a technique to reduce errors called dynamical decoupling.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The resilience level specifies how much resilience to build against errors.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] Higher levels generate more accurate results, at the expense of longer processing times.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] For further explanation of the options set in the following code, see Configure error mitigation for Qiskit Runtime.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] After the job completes, plot the results and notice that $\langle Z_0 Z_i \rangle$ ⟨Z0Zi⟩ decreases with increasing i i, even though in an ideal simulation all $\langle Z_0 Z_i \rangle$ ⟨Z0Zi⟩ should be 1.
[src:qiskit/guides-hello-world] The previous plot shows that as the distance between qubits increases, the signal decays because of the presence of noise.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Similar to the early days of classical computers, when developers had to manipulate CPU registers directly, the early interface to QPUs simply returned the raw data from the control electronics.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] This was not a big issue when QPUs lived in labs and only allowed direct access by researchers.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Acknowledging that most developers would not and should not be familiar with distilling such raw data into 0s and 1s, Qiskit introduced `backend.run`, a first abstraction for accessing QPUs in the cloud.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] This allowed developers to operate on a familiar data format and focus on the bigger picture.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] As access to QPUs became more widespread, and with more quantum algorithms being developed, again the need for a higher-level abstraction emerged.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] In response, Qiskit introduced the primitives interface, which is optimized for two core tasks in quantum algorithm development: expectation value estimation (`Estimator`) and circuit sampling (`Sampler`).
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The goal is once again to help developers to focus more on innovation and less on data conversion.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The primitives interface supersedes the `backend.run` interface, since `Sampler` provides the same direct hardware access that was offered by `backend.run`.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Computing systems are built on multiple layers of abstraction.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Abstractions allow you to focus on a particular level of detail relevant to the task at hand.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The closer you get to the hardware, the lower the level of abstraction you need (for example, you might need to move or manipulate data at the CPU instruction level).
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The more complex the task you want to perform, the higher-level the abstractions will be (for example, you could be using a programming library to perform algebraic calculations).
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] In this context, a *primitive* is the smallest processing instruction, the simplest building block from which one can create something useful for a given abstraction level.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The recent progress in quantum computing has increased the need to work at higher levels of abstraction.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] As the field moves toward larger quantum processing units (QPUs) and more complex workflows, the focus shifts from interacting with individual qubit signals to viewing quantum devices as systems that perform necessary tasks.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The two most common tasks for quantum computers are sampling quantum states and calculating expectation values.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] These tasks motivated the design of the Qiskit primitives: **Estimator** and **Sampler**.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] In short, the computational model introduced by the Qiskit primitives moves quantum programming one step closer to where classical programming is today, where the focus is less on the hardware details and more on the results you are trying to achieve.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] There are two types of Qiskit primitives: the base classes, and their implementations.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The Estimator and Sampler primitives are defined by open-source primitive base classes that live in the Qiskit SDK (in the `qiskit.primitives` module).
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Providers (such as Qiskit Runtime) can use these base classes to derive their own Sampler and Estimator implementations.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Most users will interact with provider implementations, not the base primitives.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] The `Base` primitives are abstract classes that define a common interface for implementing primitives.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] All other classes in the `qiskit.primitives` module inherit from these base classes.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Developers should use these if they are interested in creating their own primitives-based execution model for a specific provider.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] These classes might also be useful for those who want to do highly customized processing and find that the existing primitives implementations are too simple for their needs.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] General users will not directly use the base classes.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] `BaseEstimatorV1` and `BaseSamplerV1` - Although the V1 primitives are still usable, these guides focus on the V2 primitives because they are the latest and are more commonly used.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] `BaseEstimatorV2` and `BaseSamplerV2` - The Qiskit reference primitives follow these interface specifications.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] All primitives are created from the base classes; therefore, they have the same general structure and usage.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] For example, the format of the input for all Estimator primitives is the same.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] However, there are differences in implementations that make them unique.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] You can pass options to primitives to customize them to meet your needs.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] While the interface of the primitives' `run()` method is common across all implementations, their options are not.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Consult the API references for a specific primitive implementation to learn about the options it supports.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] For example, refer to the Estimator options and Sampler options topics to learn about options for the Qiskit Runtime primitives, or see the Qiskit Aer API references for the Qiskit Aer primitives options.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] With primitives, Qiskit users can write quantum code for a specific QPU without having to explicitly manage every detail.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] Also, because of the additional layer of abstraction, you might be able to more easily access advanced hardware capabilities of a given provider.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] For example, with Qiskit Runtime primitives, you can take advantage of the latest advancements in error mitigation and suppression by toggling options such as the primitive's `resilience_level`, rather than building your own implementation of these techniques.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] For hardware providers, implementing primitives natively means you can provide your users with a more “out-of-the-box” way to access your hardware features such as advanced post-processing techniques.
[src:qiskit/guides-primitives] It is therefore easier for your users to benefit from your hardware's best capabilities.
[src:qiskit/guides] Welcome to the documentation for Qiskit, its related packages, and IBM Quantum® Platform.
[src:qiskit/guides] This documentation includes how-to guides to get you started on our tools, specific use-case tutorials that include end-to-end examples, and a collection of API references.
[src:qiskit/guides] Qiskit provides a modular and extensible framework for quantum research and development across algorithms, high-performance computing, and quantum information science.
[src:qiskit/guides] With it, researchers can build, optimize, and execute quantum workflows with specialized addons, software tools, and extensive resources.
[src:qiskit/guides] Through IBM Quantum Platform, users can access quantum compute services, such as Qiskit Runtime and the Qiskit Functions Catalog, to run workloads efficiently on the IBM® fleet of quantum computers.
[src:qiskit/guides] Beyond Qiskit and its related packages is the Qiskit ecosystem, a catalog of open-source projects that interface with Qiskit to extend its functionality.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] The Qiskit SDK is the core software development kit for working with quantum computers at the level of extended (static, dynamic, and scheduled) quantum circuits, operators, and primitives.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Distributed as the Python package **qiskit**, it is an open‑source framework that allows users to construct quantum circuits, manipulate quantum operators, and interface with quantum hardware or simulators.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] The Qiskit SDK is the foundational component of the Qiskit software stack – it provides the largest set of features and acts as the base upon which other Qiskit services and modules are built.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] For example, Qiskit allows users to create quantum circuits using an intuitive Python API, then employ the transpiler to adapt and optimize these circuits for a given device’s topology and constraints (reducing gate counts or circuit depth as needed).
[src:qiskit/qiskit] The SDK also provides tools for noise modeling and supports **primitives** – basic quantum program components (such as samplers and estimators for circuit outcomes) – which serve as building blocks for higher‑level quantum algorithms and can be executed using local simulators or cloud services.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Together, these features make the Qiskit SDK a comprehensive platform for developing quantum algorithms and experiments in a hardware‑agnostic manner.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Qiskit Runtime utilizes additional classical and quantum computing resources to incorporate error‑mitigation strategies that increase the quality and accuracy of the results obtained from quantum processors.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] The runtime service also supports multiple execution modes for running quantum jobs, each suited to different use cases.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Users can execute a single **job** (a one‑off circuit or primitive call with a specified number of shots), create a **session** to run a series of jobs interactively with lower overhead between them, or submit jobs in **batch** mode for parallel execution in the queue.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] These modes allow flexibility in managing experiments – for instance, session mode enables iterative algorithms that adapt based on intermediate results, while batch mode is useful for running many independent circuits simultaneously.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] By abstracting away the details of managing cloud resources, Qiskit Serverless aims to make it easier to scale up quantum experiments and integrate them into larger computing workflows.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Qiskit Add-ons (stylized Qiskit addons) are modular, separately‑installed tools designed to extend Qiskit’s capabilities for quantum algorithm development.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] They build on Qiskit’s core framework and can be plugged into the user’s workflow to help scale or design new algorithms.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Each add‑on is distributed as an independent Python package (for example, **qiskit-addon-sqd** for the SQD tool) that can be installed via the Python Package Index (PyPI) and then used alongside Qiskit’s SDK.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] These official add-ons enhance tasks like circuit mapping, optimization, and result post‑processing while integrating seamlessly with Qiskit’s functionalities.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Each of these add-ons is maintained as an open-source extension in the GitHub Qiskit organization, with documentation and tutorials provided by IBM Quantum.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] This modular approach allows researchers to opt into advanced algorithmic techniques as needed, keeping Qiskit’s core lightweight while still enabling cutting-edge features through add-ons.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] The **Qiskit ecosystem** refers to the broader collection of open-source projects that interface with Qiskit without being part of its core SDK.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] These projects, developed by IBM Quantum or the wider community, provide additional functionality and specialized tools that complement the Qiskit framework.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] By designing Qiskit with a modular and extensible architecture, IBM has enabled external packages to integrate easily and extend its capabilities in areas like simulation, job management, and error mitigation.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] This ecosystem enhances the usability of Qiskit by addressing tasks that lie beyond the scope of the base library, allowing users to tailor their quantum computing workflows with community‑driven solutions.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] Through such ecosystem projects, Qiskit users can access extended functionality that is not included in the core SDK, thereby enhancing research and application development.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] For example, Aer enables thorough testing of algorithms in simulation, qBraid facilitates running Qiskit programs on diverse cloud hardware, and mthree helps in obtaining more accurate experimental data.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] A comprehensive catalog of Qiskit ecosystem projects is available on the Qiskit Ecosystem page, where users can discover other tools and libraries (and even contribute their own) that work in conjunction with Qiskit.
[src:qiskit/qiskit] All these ecosystem efforts contribute to a more versatile and robust quantum computing toolkit centered around Qiskit.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] If you were emailed an invitation to join an account, follow the steps in Set up your IBM Cloud account - invited users instead.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] You can run workloads on IBM® quantum processing units (QPUs) by setting up an account on IBM Cloud®.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] You will also need to install and set up Qiskit and Qiskit Runtime.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] Your user account is associated with one or more instances identified by *Cloud Resource Names* (CRNs) that give access to IBM Quantum services.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] Additionally, a unique API token (also called a key) is assigned to each account, allowing for IBM Quantum access from Qiskit.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] For instructions to choose a specific instance, see Connect to an instance.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] Log in to IBM Quantum Platform with an IBMid or Google account.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] If you don't have one, you are guided through creating one.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] Make sure that the correct account and region are selected in the account switcher in the header, as shown in the following image.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] The region controls where your jobs are run and where the job data is kept.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] You can access either region by using the same API key, but you can only see and access the instances that were created in the region that you're logged in to.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] (The IBM Quantum Platform header is shown.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] The account switcher is to the right of the search bar.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] You can create an instance from the IBM Quantum Platform Instances page.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] See Create an instance for detailed instructions.
[src:qiskit/setup-channel] If you are using a trusted Python environment, such as a personal laptop, it is recommended that you use the `save_account()` method to save your credentials locally.
